      <hedline>
        <hl1>Melting Glaciers, Imperiled Shores</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Maria Calidonna letter on January 25 article about global warming warns that many Americans living near coast would be at risk if sea levels rise as result of Antarctic melting (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Antarctica, Warming, Looks Ever More Vulnerable'' (Jan. 25): As the article points out, three major Antarctic ice shelves have collapsed in the last decade. Yet the Bush administration continues to deny the reality of global warming.</p>
        <p>These glacial changes are ominous signs; rising sea levels will eventually inundate coastal areas. According to the United States Fish and Wildlife Service, more than 75 percent of Americans will live within 50 miles of a coastline by 2010.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Antarctica, Warming, Looks Ever More Vulnerable'' (Jan. 25): As the article points out, three major Antarctic ice shelves have collapsed in the last decade. Yet the Bush administration continues to deny the reality of global warming.</p>
        <p>These glacial changes are ominous signs; rising sea levels will eventually inundate coastal areas. According to the United States Fish and Wildlife Service, more than 75 percent of Americans will live within 50 miles of a coastline by 2010.</p>
        <p>Though this future catastrophe won't occur unexpectedly like the tsunami that recently hit southern Asia, it may be just as devastating.</p>
        <p>MARIA CALIDONNA  Cortlandt Manor, N.Y.</p>
      </block>
